# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: thread-matter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group defined encapsulation, header compression, neighbor discovery and other mechanisms that allow IPv6 to operate over IEEE 802.15.4 based networks.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Although IPv4 and IPv6 protocols do not generally care about the physical and MAC layers they operate over, the low-power devices and small packet size defined by IEEE 802.15.4 make it desirable to adapt to these layers.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The base specification developed by the 6LoWPAN IETF group is RFC 4944 (updated by RFC 6282 with header compression, RFC 6775 with neighbor discovery optimization, RFC 8931 with selective fragment recovery and with smaller changes in RFC 8025 and RFC 8066).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The problem statement document is RFC 4919.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 over Bluetooth Low Energy using 6LoWPAN techniques is described in RFC 7668.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The targets for IPv6 networking for low-power radio communication are devices that need wireless connectivity to many other devices at lower data rates for devices with very limited power consumption.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The header compression mechanisms in RFC 6282 are used to allow IPv6 packets to travel over such networks.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 is also in use on the smart grid enabling smart meters and other devices to build a micro mesh network before sending the data back to the billing system using the IPv6 backbone.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Some of these networks run over IEEE 802.15.4 radios, and therefore use the header compression and fragmentation as specified by RFC6282.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Thread is a standard from a group of more than fifty companies for a protocol running over 6LoWPAN to enable home automation.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The specification is available at no cost as of 24 June 2022, but paid membership is required to implement the protocol.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 2015-10-29.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The protocol most directly competes with Z-Wave and Zigbee IP.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] In IoT device communications using the Matter standard, Thread is one of two possible wireless transport layers.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] As with all link-layer mappings of IP, RFC4944 provides a number of functions.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Beyond the usual differences between L2 and L3 networks, mapping from the IPv6 network to the IEEE 802.15.4 network poses additional design challenges (see RFC 4919 for an overview).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 requires the link maximum transmission unit (MTU) to be at least 1280 octets.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] In contrast, IEEE 802.15.4's standard frame size is 127 octets.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] A maximum frame overhead of 25 octets and an optional but highly recommended security feature at the link layer poses an additional overhead of up to 21 octets are for AES-CCM-128.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] This leaves only 81 octets for the upper layers.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Since this is so much less than 1280, 6LoWPAN defines a fragmentation and reassembly layer.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Further, the standard IPv6 Header is 40 octets long, so header compression is defined as well.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are assigned 128 bit IP addresses in a hierarchical manner, through an arbitrary length network prefix.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices may use either of IEEE 64 bit extended addresses or, after an association event, 16 bit addresses that are unique within a PAN.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] There is also a PAN-ID for a group of physically collocated IEEE 802.15.4 devices.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 devices are intentionally constrained in form factor to reduce costs (allowing for large-scale network of many devices), reduce power consumption (allowing battery powered devices) and allow flexibility of installation (e.g. small devices for body-worn networks).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] On the other hand, wired nodes in the IP domain are not constrained in this way; they can be larger and make use of mains power supplies.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 nodes are geared towards attaining high speeds.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Algorithms and protocols implemented at the higher layers such as TCP kernel of the TCP/IP are optimized to handle typical network problems such as congestion.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] In IEEE 802.15.4-compliant devices, energy conservation and code-size optimization remain at the top of the agenda.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] An adaptation mechanism to allow interoperability between IPv6 domain and the IEEE 802.15.4 can best be viewed as a layer problem.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Identifying the functionality of this layer and defining newer packet formats, if needed, is an enticing research area.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] RFC 4944 proposes an adaptation layer to allow the transmission of IPv6 datagrams over IEEE 802.15.4 networks.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The management of addresses for devices that communicate across the two dissimilar domains of IPv6 and IEEE 802.15.4 is cumbersome, if not exhaustingly complex.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Several routing protocols have been proposed by the 6LoWPAN community such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] However, only two routing protocols are currently legitimate for large-scale deployments: LOADng standardized by the ITU under the recommendation ITU-T G.9903 and RPL standardized by the IETF ROLL working group.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN routing scheme can be carried out in two different ways: *mesh-under* and *route-over*.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Initially, several routing protocols were developed by the 6LoWPAN community, such as LOAD, DYMO-LOW, HI-LOW .
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Since IP-enabled devices may require the formation of ad hoc networks, the current state of neighboring devices and the services hosted by such devices will need to be known.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPv6 neighbour discovery extensions is an internet draft proposed as a contribution in this area.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IEEE 802.15.4 nodes can operate in either secure mode or non-secure mode.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 defines the IPv6 header compression mechanism for LowPAN: LOWPAN_HC1.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] It also includes compression of the UDP header over 4 bytes, but does not allow compression of the *Checksum*.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Additionally, it restricts the range of UDP ports from 61616 to 61631 in order to compress this value to 4 bits.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] This IPv6 header compression can only be applied to local link addresses.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] To overcome this problem, an IETF LOWPAN_HC1g draft was published.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] LOWPAN_HC1g applies to global addresses for IP multi-hop communications.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] These two compression mechanisms (LOWPAN_HC1 and LOWPAN_HC1g) are complementary.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] It is therefore necessary to implement both.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Today the proposal of the 6LoWPAN group is to use LOWPAN_IPHC.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] IPHC bytes result from compression of the IPv6 header.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] They mainly integrate information from quality of service (DSCP and ECN), next headers, number of hops and compressed source/destination addresses.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The example below shows the increase in payload compared to the original problem (see 1re figure).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] This payload is in the best case 70 to 75 bytes.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Indeed, if we add the fragmentation information as indicated in the paragraph above, it will decrease to 65-70 bytes for this scenario.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Technological developments in the 1990s (miniaturization of electronics, deployment of new wireless networks and embedded systems) enabled the emergence of new applications for sensor and actuator networks.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] With the advent of wireless technologies, the first solutions used were completely proprietary (for example Z-Wave or EnOcean).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] With the standard IEEE 802.15.4 (radio use of wireless sensors) new proprietary standards have appeared (for example, ZigBee, WirelessHART **(in)**, etc.).
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] When first thinking about wireless sensor networking, 6LoWPAN was born from a simple idea: why reinvent a protocol when we already have IP?
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Geoff Mulligan proposes the use of IP on 802.15.4 for sensor type equipment.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] , "robust header compression") of IETF were interested.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS released on the implementation of "Arch Rock Company: Primer Pack/IP".
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] A first implementation of 6LoWPAN on TinyOS is available on the implementation of "Sensinode Company: NanoStack v0.9.4".
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The 6LoWPAN group publishes the RFC 4919 to ensure the interoperability of the network layer.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] There RFC 4944 sees the light of day, based on the RFC4919.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] This should allow direct connectivity to the Internet of LoWPAN equipment via IPv6 and replace them communication protocols owners like ZigBee,, which was developed after the end of the Smart Dust project.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] The IETF launches the ROLL Working Group.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] , "IP for Smart Objects"), chaired by Geoff Mulligan, is created to promote the use of IP in smart objects.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Smart objects are small type objects switch, detector more commonly called sensors.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] To develop smart grids, President Obama announces an investment of $3.4 billion.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Study demonstrates significant economic prospects in IoT.
[src:thread-matter/6lowpan] Cisco buys the company Arch Rock (one of the leaders in BAC applications for WSN), which strengthens the strategic alliance previously signed between Cisco and Itron (metering specialist smart grid),.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The **Connectivity Standards Alliance** (**CSA**), formerly known as the **Zigbee Alliance**, is a group of companies that maintain and publish the Zigbee and Matter standards, along with several others.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] Over the years, the Alliance's membership has grown to over 600 companies, including the likes of Amazon, Apple, Comcast, Google, Yandex, Ikea, Heiman, and Samsung SmartThings.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The CSA has four levels of membership: associate, adopter, participant, and promoter.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The Alliance also has two regional member groups in China and Europe: The Connectivity Standards Alliance Member Group China (CMGC) is formed by members with a focus on promoting Alliance technologies in the China market.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The Europe Interest Group (EIG) consisting of 98+ member companies and 216 individual members has a focus on the European market.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The name Zigbee is a registered trademark of this group, and is not a single technical standard.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The organization publishes application profiles that allow multiple original equipment manufacturer (OEM) vendors to create interoperable products.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The relationship between IEEE 802.15.4 and Zigbee is similar to that between IEEE 802.11 and the Wi-Fi Alliance.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The requirements for membership in the Alliance cause problems for free-software developers working with Zigbee because the annual fee conflicts with the GNU General Public Licence.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The requirements for developers to join the CSA also conflict with most other free-software licenses.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] The CSA board of directors has been asked to make their license compatible with GPL, but refused.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] Bluetooth has GPL-licensed implementations.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] However, the main Matter SDK is licensed under Apache 2.0 alongside the TypeScript and Rust implementations.
[src:thread-matter/connectivity-standards-alliance] On May 11, 2021, the Zigbee Alliance announced its rebranding to *Connectivity Standards Alliance*.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE standard 802.15.4 is intended to offer the fundamental lower network layers of a type of wireless personal area network (WPAN), which focuses on low-cost, low-speed ubiquitous communication between devices.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It can be contrasted with other approaches, such as Wi-Fi, which offers more bandwidth and requires more power.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The emphasis is on very low-cost communication of nearby devices with little to no underlying infrastructure, intending to exploit this to lower power consumption even more.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The basic framework conceives a 10-meter communications range with line of sight at a transfer rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Bandwidth tradeoffs are possible to favor more radically embedded devices with even lower power requirements for increased battery operating time, through the definition of not one, but several physical layers.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Lower transfer rates of 20 and 40 kbit/s were initially defined, with the 100 kbit/s rate being added in the current revision.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Even lower rates can be used, which results in lower power consumption.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] As already mentioned, the main goal of IEEE 802.15.4 regarding WPANs is the emphasis on achieving low manufacturing and operating costs through the use of relatively simple transceivers, while enabling application flexibility and adaptability.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Integrated support for secure communications.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Power management functions to adjust compromises of link speed and quality and energy detection.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Support for time- and data-rate–sensitive applications through the ability to operate with either CSMA/CA or TDMA access modes.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The TDMA mode of operation is supported via the GTS feature of the standard.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4-conformant devices may use one of three possible frequency bands for operation (868/915/2450 MHz).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Devices are designed to interact with each other over a conceptually simple wireless network.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The definition of the network layers is based on the OSI model; although only the lower layers are defined in the standard, interaction with upper layers is intended, possibly using an IEEE 802.2 logical link control sublayer accessing the MAC through a convergence sublayer.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Implementations may rely on external devices or be purely embedded, self-functioning devices.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The *physical layer* (PHY) provides the data transmission service.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It also, provides an interface to the *physical layer management entity*, which offers access to every physical layer management function and maintains a database of information on related personal area networks.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Thus, the PHY manages the physical radio transceiver, performs channel selection along with energy and signal management functions.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] An optional alternative 868/915 MHz layer is defined using a combination of binary keying and amplitude-shift keying (thus based on parallel, not sequential, spread spectrum; PSSS).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Dynamic switching between supported 868/915 MHz PHYs is possible.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Beyond these three bands, the IEEE 802.15.4c study group considered the newly opened 314–316 MHz, 430–434 MHz, and 779–787 MHz bands in China, while the IEEE 802.15 Task Group 4d defined an amendment to to support the new 950–956 MHz band in Japan.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The first standard amendments by these groups were released in April 2009.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4e was chartered to define a MAC amendment to the existing standard 802.15.4-2006 which adopts a channel hopping strategy to improve support for the industrial market.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Channel hopping increases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] On February 6, 2012, the IEEE Standards Association Board approved IEEE 802.15.4e which concluded all Task Group 4e efforts.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The medium access control (MAC) enables the transmission of MAC frames through the use of the physical channel.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Besides the data service, it offers a management interface and itself manages access to the physical channel and network beaconing.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It also controls frame validation, guarantees time slots and handles node associations.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Finally, it offers hook points for secure services.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Note that the IEEE 802.15 standard does *not* use 802.1d or IEEE standard 802.15.4q-2016; i.e., it does not exchange standard Ethernet frames.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The physical frame-format is specified in IEEE standard 802.15.4-2011 in section 5.2.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It is tailored to the fact that most IEEE 802.15.4 PHYs only support frames of up to 127 bytes (adaptation layer protocols such as the IETF's 6LoWPAN provide fragmentation schemes to support larger network layer packets).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] No higher-level layers or interoperability sublayers are defined in the standard.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Other specifications, such as Zigbee, SNAP, and 6LoWPAN/Thread, build on this standard.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] RIOT, OpenWSN, TinyOS, Unison RTOS, DSPnano RTOS, nanoQplus, Contiki and Zephyr operating systems also use some components of IEEE standard 802.15.4-2020 hardware and software.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The standard defines two types of network node.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The first one is the **full-function device** (FFD).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It can serve as the coordinator of a personal area network just as it may function as a common node.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] It implements a general model of communication which allows it to talk to any other device: it may also relay messages, in which case it is dubbed a coordinator (PAN coordinator when it is in charge of the whole network).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] On the other hand, there are **reduced-function devices** (RFD).
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] These are meant to be extremely simple devices with very modest resource and communication requirements; due to this, they can only communicate with FFDs and can never act as coordinators.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Networks can be built as either peer-to-peer or star networks.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] However, every network needs at least one FFD to work as the coordinator of the network.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Networks are thus formed by groups of devices separated by suitable distances.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Each device has a unique 64-bit identifier, and if some conditions are met, short 16-bit identifiers can be used within a restricted environment.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Namely, within each PAN domain, communications will probably use short identifiers.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] A more structured **star** pattern is also supported, where the coordinator of the network will necessarily be the central node.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Such a network can originate when an FFD decides to create its own PAN and declare itself its coordinator, after choosing a unique PAN identifier.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] After that, other devices can join the network, which is fully independent from all other star networks.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Frames are the basic unit of data transport, of which there are four fundamental types (data, acknowledgment, beacon and MAC command frames), which provide a reasonable tradeoff between simplicity and robustness.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Additionally, a superframe structure, defined by the coordinator, may be used, in which case two beacons act as its limits and provide synchronization to other devices as well as configuration information.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] A superframe consists of sixteen equal-length slots, which can be further divided into an active part and an inactive part, during which the coordinator may enter power saving mode, not needing to control its network.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Within superframes contention occurs between their limits, and is resolved by CSMA/CA.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Every transmission must end before the arrival of the second beacon.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] As mentioned before, applications with well-defined bandwidth needs can use up to seven domains of one or more contentionless guaranteed time slots, trailing at the end of the superframe.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The first part of the superframe must be sufficient to give service to the network structure and its devices.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Superframes are typically utilized within the context of low-latency devices, whose associations must be kept even if inactive for long periods of time.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers to the coordinator require a beacon synchronization phase, if applicable, followed by CSMA/CA transmission (by means of slots if superframes are in use); acknowledgment is optional.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers from the coordinator usually follow device requests: if beacons are in use, these are used to signal requests; the coordinator acknowledges the request and then sends the data in packets which are acknowledged by the device.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The same is done when superframes are not in use, only in this case there are no beacons to keep track of pending messages.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Point-to-point networks may either use unslotted CSMA/CA or synchronization mechanisms; in this case, communication between any two devices is possible, whereas in "structured" modes one of the devices must be the network coordinator.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] In general, all implemented procedures follow a typical request-confirm/indication-response classification.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] The physical medium is accessed through a CSMA/CA access method.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Networks which are not using beaconing mechanisms utilize an unslotted variation which is based on the listening of the medium, leveraged by a random exponential backoff algorithm; acknowledgments do not adhere to this discipline.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Common data transmission utilizes unallocated slots when beaconing is in use; again, confirmations do not follow the same process.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Confirmation messages may be optional under certain circumstances, in which case a success assumption is made.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Whatever the case, if a device is unable to process a frame at a given time, it simply does not confirm its reception: timeout-based retransmission can be performed a number of times, following after that a decision of whether to abort or keep trying.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Because the predicted environment of these devices demands maximization of battery life, the protocols tend to favor the methods which lead to it, implementing periodic checks for pending messages, the frequency of which depends on application needs.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Regarding secure communications, the MAC sublayer offers facilities which can be harnessed by upper layers to achieve the desired level of security.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Higher-layer processes may specify keys to perform symmetric cryptography to protect the payload and restrict it to a group of devices or just a point-to-point link; these groups of devices can be specified in access control lists.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] Furthermore, MAC computes *freshness checks* between successive receptions to ensure that presumably old frames, or data which is no longer considered valid, does not transcend to higher layers.
[src:thread-matter/ieee-802-15-4] In addition to this secure mode, there is another, insecure MAC mode, which allows access control lists merely as a means to decide on the acceptance of frames according to their (presumed) source.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Devices on the Internet are assigned a unique IP address for identification and location definition.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] With the rapid growth of the Internet after commercialization in the 1990s, it became evident that far more addresses would be needed to connect devices than the 4 billion (232) addresses IPv4 made available.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By 1998, the IETF had formalized the successor protocol, IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This uses 128-bit addresses, yielding an address space of 2128, 1038, or 340 undecillion total addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Several transition mechanisms have been devised to allow IPv4 and IPv6 to interoperate, but IPv6 is not backwards-compatible with IPv4 and the two do not interoperate directly.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 provides other technical benefits in addition to a larger addressing space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In particular, it permits hierarchical address allocation methods that facilitate route aggregation across the Internet, and thus limit the expansion of routing tables.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The use of multicast addressing is expanded and simplified, and provides additional optimization for the delivery of services.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Device mobility, security, and configuration aspects have been considered in the design of the protocol.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 addresses are represented as eight groups of four hexadecimal digits each, separated by colons.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 is an Internet Layer protocol for packet-switched internetworking and provides end-to-end datagram transmission across multiple IP networks, closely adhering to the design principles developed in the previous version of the protocol, Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In addition to offering more addresses, IPv6 also implements features not present in IPv4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It simplifies aspects of address configuration, network renumbering, and router announcements when changing network connectivity providers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It simplifies packet processing in routers by placing the responsibility for packet fragmentation in the endpoints.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IPv6 subnet size is standardized by fixing the size of the host identifier portion of an address to 64 bits.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The addressing architecture of IPv6 allows three different types of transmission: unicast, anycast and multicast.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 does not implement broadcast, and therefore has no notion of a broadcast address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) was the first publicly used version of the Internet Protocol.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv4 was developed as a research project by the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA), a United States Department of Defense agency, before becoming the foundation for the Internet and the World Wide Web.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv4 includes an addressing system that uses numerical identifiers consisting of 32 bits.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] These addresses are typically displayed in dot-decimal notation as decimal values of four octets, each in the range 0 to 255, or 8 bits per number.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Thus, IPv4 provides an addressing capability of 232 or approximately 4.3 billion addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Address exhaustion was not initially a concern in IPv4 as this version was originally presumed to be a test of DARPA's networking concepts.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] During the first decade of operation of the Internet, it became apparent that methods had to be developed to conserve address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In the early 1990s, even after the redesign of the addressing system using a classless network model, it became clear that this would not suffice to prevent IPv4 address exhaustion, and that further changes to the Internet infrastructure were needed.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The last unassigned top-level address blocks of 16 million IPv4 addresses were allocated in February 2011 by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) to the five regional Internet registries (RIRs).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] At that point, each RIR still had available address pools and was expected to continue with standard address allocation policies until one */8* Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) block remained.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] After that, only blocks of 1,024 addresses (/22) were provided from the RIRs to a local Internet registry (LIR).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] RIPE NCC was the last to do so; it announced that it had fully run out of IPv4 addresses on 25 November 2019, and called for greater progress on the adoption of IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] On the Internet, data is transmitted in the form of network packets.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 specifies a new packet format, designed to minimize packet header processing by routers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Because the headers of IPv4 packets and IPv6 packets are significantly different, the two protocols are not interoperable.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The main advantage of IPv6 over IPv4 is its larger address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The size of an IPv6 address is 128 bits, compared to 32 bits in IPv4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The address space therefore has 2128 addresses (340 undecillion, approximately 3.4×1038).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Some blocks of this space and some specific addresses are reserved for special uses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] While this address space is very large, it was not the intent of the designers of IPv6 to assure geographical saturation with usable addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Rather, the longer addresses simplify allocation of addresses, enable efficient route aggregation, and allow implementation of special addressing features.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In IPv4, complex Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) methods were developed to make the best use of the small address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The network identifier part of the address in IPv6 is usually 264 addresses, about four billion times the size of the entire IPv4 address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Thus, actual address space utilization will be small in IPv6, but network management and routing efficiency are improved by the large subnet space and hierarchical route aggregation.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Multicasting, the transmission of a packet to multiple destinations in a single send operation, is part of the base specification in IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In IPv4 this is an optional (although commonly implemented) feature.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 multicast addressing has features and protocols in common with IPv4 multicast, but also provides changes and improvements by eliminating the need for certain protocols.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 does not implement traditional IP broadcast, i.e. the transmission of a packet to all hosts on the attached link using a special *broadcast address*, and therefore does not define broadcast addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In IPv6, the same result is achieved by sending a packet to the link-local *all nodes* multicast group at address *ff02::1*, which is analogous to IPv4 multicasting to address *224.0.0.1*.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 also provides for new multicast implementations, including embedding rendezvous point addresses in an IPv6 multicast group address, which simplifies the deployment of inter-domain solutions.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In IPv4 it is very difficult for an organization to get even one globally routable multicast group assignment, and the implementation of inter-domain solutions is arcane.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Unicast address assignments by a local Internet registry for IPv6 have at least a 64-bit routing prefix, yielding the smallest subnet size available in IPv6 (also 64 bits).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] With such an assignment it is possible to embed the unicast address prefix into the IPv6 multicast address format, while still providing a 32-bit block, the least significant bits of the address, or approximately 4.2 billion multicast group identifiers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Thus each user of an IPv6 subnet automatically has available a set of globally routable source-specific multicast groups for multicast applications.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 hosts configure themselves automatically.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Every interface has a self-generated link-local address and, when connected to a network, conflict resolution is performed and routers provide network prefixes via router advertisements.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Stateless configuration of routers can be achieved with a special router renumbering protocol.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] When necessary, hosts may configure additional stateful addresses via Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol version 6 (DHCPv6) or static addresses manually.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Like IPv4, IPv6 supports globally unique IP addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The design of IPv6 intended to re-emphasize the end-to-end principle of network design that was originally conceived during the establishment of the early Internet by rendering network address translation obsolete.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Therefore, every device on the network is globally addressable directly from any other device.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A stable, unique, globally addressable IP address would facilitate tracking a device across networks.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Therefore, such addresses are a particular privacy concern for mobile devices, such as laptops and cell phones.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] To address these privacy concerns, the SLAAC protocol includes what are typically called "privacy addresses" or, more correctly, "temporary addresses".
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Temporary addresses are random and unstable.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A typical consumer device generates a new temporary address daily and will ignore traffic addressed to an old address after one week.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Temporary addresses are used by default by Windows since XP SP1, macOS since (Mac OS X) 10.7, Android since 4.0, and iOS since version 4.3.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Use of temporary addresses by Linux distributions varies.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Renumbering an existing network for a new connectivity provider with different routing prefixes is a major effort with IPv4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] With IPv6, however, changing the prefix announced by a few routers can in principle renumber an entire network, since the host identifiers (the least-significant 64 bits of an address) can be independently self-configured by a host.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The SLAAC address generation method is implementation-dependent.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IETF recommends that addresses be deterministic but semantically opaque.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) was originally developed for IPv6, but found widespread deployment first in IPv4, for which it was re-engineered.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] However, as of RFC 4301 IPv6 protocol implementations that do implement IPsec need to implement IKEv2 and need to support a minimum set of cryptographic algorithms.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This requirement will help to make IPsec implementations more interoperable between devices from different vendors.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IPsec Authentication Header (AH) and the Encapsulating Security Payload header (ESP) are implemented as IPv6 extension headers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The packet header in IPv6 is simpler than the IPv4 header.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Many rarely used fields have been moved to optional header extensions.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IPv6 packet header has simplified the process of packet forwarding by routers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Although IPv6 packet headers are at least twice the size of IPv4 packet headers, processing of packets that only contain the base IPv6 header by routers may, in some cases, be more efficient, because less processing is required in routers due to the headers being aligned to match common word sizes.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] However, many devices implement IPv6 support in software (as opposed to hardware), thus resulting in very bad packet processing performance.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Additionally, for many implementations, the use of Extension Headers causes packets to be processed by a router's CPU, leading to poor performance or even security issues.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Moreover, an IPv6 header does not include a checksum.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IPv4 header checksum is calculated for the IPv4 header, and has to be recalculated by routers every time the time to live (called hop limit in the IPv6 protocol) is reduced by one.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The absence of a checksum in the IPv6 header furthers the end-to-end principle of Internet design, which envisioned that most processing in the network occurs in the leaf nodes.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Integrity protection for the data that is encapsulated in the IPv6 packet is assumed to be assured by both the link layer or error detection in higher-layer protocols, namely the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) on the transport layer.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Thus, while IPv4 allowed UDP datagram headers to have no checksum (indicated by 0 in the header field), IPv6 requires a checksum in UDP headers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 routers do not perform IP fragmentation.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 hosts are required to do one of the following: perform Path MTU Discovery, perform end-to-end fragmentation, or send packets no larger than the default maximum transmission unit (MTU), which is 1280 octets.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Unlike mobile IPv4, mobile IPv6 avoids triangular routing and is therefore as efficient as native IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 routers may also allow entire subnets to move to a new router connection point without renumbering.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IPv6 packet header has a minimum size of 40 octets (320 bits).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This provides the opportunity to extend the protocol in the future without affecting the core packet structure.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] However, RFC 7872 notes that some network operators drop IPv6 packets with extension headers when they traverse transit autonomous systems.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv4 limits packets to 65,535 (216 − 1) octets of payload.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] An IPv6 node can optionally handle packets over this limit, referred to as jumbograms, which can be as large as 4,294,967,295 (232 − 1) octets.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The use of jumbograms may improve performance over high-MTU links.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The use of jumbograms is indicated by the Jumbo Payload Option extension header.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] An IPv6 packet has two parts: a header and payload.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The header consists of a fixed portion with minimal functionality required for all packets and may be followed by optional extensions to implement special features.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The fixed header occupies the first 40 octets (320 bits) of the IPv6 packet.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It contains the source and destination addresses, traffic class, hop count, and the type of the optional extension or payload which follows the header.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This *Next Header* field tells the receiver how to interpret the data which follows the header.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If the packet contains options, this field contains the option type of the next option.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The "Next Header" field of the last option points to the upper-layer protocol that is carried in the packet's payload.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The current use of the IPv6 Traffic Class field divides this between a 6 bit Differentiated Services Code Point. and a 2-bit Explicit Congestion Notification field.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Extension headers carry options that are used for special treatment of a packet in the network, e.g., for routing, fragmentation, and for security using the IPsec framework.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Without special options, a payload must be less than 64kB.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] With a Jumbo Payload option (in a *Hop-By-Hop Options* extension header), the payload must be less than 4 GB.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Unlike with IPv4, routers never fragment a packet.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Hosts are expected to use Path MTU Discovery to make their packets small enough to reach the destination without needing to be fragmented.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The design of the IPv6 address space implements a different design philosophy than in IPv4, in which subnetting was used to improve the efficiency of utilization of the small address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In IPv6, the address space is deemed large enough for the foreseeable future, and a local area subnet always uses 64 bits for the host portion of the address, designated as the interface identifier, while the most-significant 64 bits are used as the routing prefix.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] While the myth has existed regarding IPv6 subnets being impossible to scan, RFC 7707 notes that patterns resulting from some IPv6 address configuration techniques and algorithms allow address scanning in many real-world scenarios.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The 128 bits of an IPv6 address are represented in 8 groups of 16 bits each.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Each group is written as four hexadecimal digits (sometimes called *hextets* or more formally *hexadectets* and informally a *quibble* or *quad-nibble*) and the groups are separated by colons (:).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] As an IPv6 address may have more than one representation, the IETF has issued a proposed standard for representing them in text.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Because IPv6 addresses contain colons, and URLs use colons to separate the host from the port number, an IPv6 address used as the host-part of a URL should be enclosed in square brackets, e.g. http://[2001:db8:4006:812::200e] or http://[2001:db8:4006:812::200e]:8080/path/page.html.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] All interfaces of IPv6 hosts require a link-local address, which have the prefix *fe80::/10*.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This prefix is followed by 54 bits that can be used for subnetting, although they are typically set to zeros, and a 64-bit interface identifier.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The host can compute and assign the Interface identifier by itself without the presence or cooperation of an external network component like a DHCP server, in a process called *link-local address autoconfiguration*.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The lower 64 bits of the link-local address (the suffix) were originally derived from the MAC address of the underlying network interface card.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] As this method of assigning addresses would cause undesirable address changes when faulty network cards were replaced, and as it also suffered from a number of security and privacy issues, RFC 8064 has replaced the original MAC-based method with the hash-based method specified in RFC 7217.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 uses a new mechanism for mapping IP addresses to link-layer addresses (e.g.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] MAC addresses), because it does not support the broadcast addressing method, on which the functionality of the Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) in IPv4 is based.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 implements the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP, ND) in the link layer, which relies on ICMPv6 and multicast transmission.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 hosts verify the uniqueness of their IPv6 addresses in a local area network (LAN) by sending a neighbor solicitation message asking for the link-layer address of the IP address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If any other host in the LAN is using that address, it responds.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A host bringing up a new IPv6 interface first generates a unique link-local address using one of several mechanisms designed to generate a unique address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Should a non-unique address be detected, the host can try again with a newly generated address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Once a unique link-local address is established, the IPv6 host determines whether the LAN is connected on this link to any router interface that supports IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It does so by sending out an ICMPv6 router solicitation message to the all-routers multicast group with its link-local address as source.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If there is no answer after a predetermined number of attempts, the host concludes that no routers are connected.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If it does get a response, known as a router advertisement, from a router, the response includes the network configuration information to allow establishment of a globally unique address with an appropriate unicast network prefix.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The assignment procedure for global addresses is similar to local-address construction.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The prefix is supplied from router advertisements on the network.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Multiple prefix announcements cause multiple addresses to be configured.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Stateless address autoconfiguration (SLAAC) requires a */64* address block.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Local Internet registries are assigned at least */32* blocks, which they divide among subordinate networks.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The initial recommendation of September 2001 stated assignment of a */48* subnet to end-consumer sites.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In March 2011 this recommendation was refined: The IETF "recommends giving home sites significantly more than a single */64*, but does not recommend that every home site be given a */48* either".
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Blocks of */56*s are specifically considered.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It remains to be seen whether ISPs will honor this recommendation.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] For example, during initial trials, Comcast customers were given a single */64* network.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In the Domain Name System (DNS), hostnames are mapped to IPv6 addresses by AAAA ("quad-A") resource records.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] For reverse resolution, the IETF reserved the domain ip6.arpa, where the name space is hierarchically divided by the 1-digit hexadecimal representation of nibble units (4 bits) of the IPv6 address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] When a dual-stack host queries a DNS server to resolve a fully qualified domain name (FQDN), the DNS client of the host sends two DNS requests, one querying AAAA records and the other querying A records, in that order, by default.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If both types of addresses are returned by the DNS, and there is a route for it, the IPv6 address is preferred over the IPv4 address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] However, the host operating system may be configured with an alternate preference for address selection.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] An alternative record type was used in early DNS implementations for IPv6, designed to facilitate network renumbering.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The *A6* resource record was used for the forward lookup, completed with a number of other innovations such as *bit-string labels* and *DNAME* records.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] After a discussion of the pros and cons of both schemes,) the use of A6 resource records has been deprecated to experimental status.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] IPv6 is not foreseen to supplant IPv4 instantaneously.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Both protocols will continue to operate simultaneously for some time.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Therefore, IPv6 transition mechanisms are needed to enable IPv6 hosts to reach IPv4 services and to allow isolated IPv6 hosts and networks to reach each other over IPv4 infrastructure.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] According to Silvia Hagen, a dual-stack implementation of the IPv4 and IPv6 on devices is the easiest way to migrate to IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Many other transition mechanisms use tunneling to encapsulate IPv6 traffic within IPv4 networks and vice versa.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This is an imperfect solution, which reduces the maximum transmission unit (MTU) of a link and therefore complicates Path MTU Discovery, and may increase latency.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Dual-stack IP implementations provide complete IPv4 and IPv6 protocol stacks in the operating system of a computer or network device on top of the common physical layer implementation, such as Ethernet.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This permits dual-stack hosts to participate in IPv6 and IPv4 networks simultaneously.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A device with dual-stack implementation in the operating system has an IPv4 and IPv6 address, and can communicate with other nodes in the LAN or the Internet using either IPv4 or IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The DNS protocol is used by both IP protocols to resolve fully qualified domain names and IP addresses, but dual stack requires that the resolving DNS server can resolve both types of addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Such a dual-stack DNS server holds IPv4 addresses in the A records and IPv6 addresses in the AAAA records.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Depending on the destination that is to be resolved, a DNS name server may return an IPv4 or IPv6 IP address, or both.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A default address selection mechanism, or preferred protocol, needs to be configured either on hosts or the DNS server.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The IETF has published Happy Eyeballs to assist dual-stack applications, so that they can connect using both IPv4 and IPv6, but prefer an IPv6 connection if it is available.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] However, dual-stack also needs to be implemented on all routers between the host and the service for which the DNS server has returned an IPv6 address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Dual-stack clients should be configured to prefer IPv6 only if the network is able to forward IPv6 packets using the IPv6 versions of routing protocols.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] When dual-stack network protocols are in place the application layer can be migrated to IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] While dual-stack is supported by major operating system and network device vendors, legacy networking hardware and servers do not support IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Internet service providers (ISPs) are increasingly providing their business and private customers with public-facing IPv6 global unicast addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] If IPv4 is still used in the local area network (LAN), however, and the ISP can only provide one public-facing IPv6 address, the IPv4 LAN addresses are translated into the public facing IPv6 address using NAT64, a network address translation (NAT) mechanism.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Some ISPs cannot provide their customers with public-facing IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, thus supporting dual-stack networking, because some ISPs have exhausted their globally routable IPv4 address pool.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Meanwhile, ISP customers are still trying to reach IPv4 web servers and other destinations.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A significant percentage of ISPs in all regional Internet registry (RIR) zones have obtained IPv6 address space.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This includes many of the world's major ISPs and mobile network operators, such as Verizon Wireless, StarHub Cable, Chubu Telecommunications, Kabel Deutschland, Swisscom, T-Mobile, Internode and Telefónica.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] While some ISPs still allocate customers only IPv4 addresses, many ISPs allocate their customers only an IPv6 or dual-stack IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] ISPs report the share of IPv6 traffic from customers over their network to be anything between 20% and 40%, but by mid-2017 IPv6 traffic still only accounted for a fraction of total traffic at several large Internet exchange points (IXPs).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] AMS-IX reported it to be 2% and SeattleIX reported 7%.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A 2017 survey found that many DSL customers that were served by a dual stack ISP did not request DNS servers to resolve fully qualified domain names into IPv6 addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The survey also found that the majority of traffic from IPv6-ready web-server resources were still requested and served over IPv4, mostly due to ISP customers that did not use the dual stack facility provided by their ISP and to a lesser extent due to customers of IPv4-only ISPs.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The technical basis for tunneling, or encapsulating IPv6 packets in IPv4 packets, is outlined in RFC 4213.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] When the Internet backbone was IPv4-only, one of the frequently used tunneling protocols was 6to4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Teredo tunneling was also frequently used for integrating IPv6 LANs with the IPv4 Internet backbone.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Teredo is outlined in RFC 4380 and allows IPv6 local area networks to tunnel over IPv4 networks, by encapsulating IPv6 packets within UDP.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The Teredo relay is an IPv6 router that mediates between a Teredo server and the native IPv6 network.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] It was expected that 6to4 and Teredo would be widely deployed until ISP networks would switch to native IPv6, but by 2014 Google Statistics showed that the use of both mechanisms had dropped to almost 0.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Hybrid dual-stack IPv6/IPv4 implementations recognize a special class of addresses, the IPv4-mapped IPv6 addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] These addresses are typically written with a 96-bit prefix in the standard IPv6 format, and the remaining 32 bits are written in the customary dot-decimal notation of IPv4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Addresses in this group consist of an 80-bit prefix of zeros, the next 16 bits are ones, and the remaining, least-significant 32 bits contain the IPv4 address.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A previous format, called "IPv4-compatible IPv6 address", was *::192.0.2.128*; however, this method is deprecated.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Because of the significant internal differences between IPv4 and IPv6 protocol stacks, some of the lower-level functionality available to programmers in the IPv6 stack does not work the same when used with IPv4-mapped addresses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Some common IPv6 stacks do not implement the IPv4-mapped address feature, either because the IPv6 and IPv4 stacks are separate implementations (e.g., Microsoft Windows 2000, XP, and Server 2003), or because of security concerns (OpenBSD).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] On these operating systems, a program must open a separate socket for each IP protocol it uses.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] On some systems, e.g., the Linux kernel, NetBSD, and FreeBSD, this feature is controlled by the socket option IPV6_V6ONLY.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The address prefix *64:ff9b::/96* is a class of IPv4-embedded IPv6 addresses for use in NAT64 transition methods.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A number of security implications may arise from the use of IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Some of them may be related with the IPv6 protocols themselves, while others may be related with implementation flaws.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The addition of nodes having IPv6 enabled by default by the software manufacturer may result in the inadvertent creation of *shadow networks*, causing IPv6 traffic flowing into networks having only IPv4 security management in place.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] This may also occur with operating system upgrades, when the newer operating system enables IPv6 by default, while the older one did not.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Failing to update the security infrastructure to accommodate IPv6 can lead to IPv6 traffic bypassing it.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Shadow networks have occurred on business networks in which enterprises are replacing Windows XP systems that do not have an IPv6 stack enabled by default, with Windows 7 systems, that do.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Some IPv6 stack implementors have therefore recommended disabling IPv4 mapped addresses and instead using a dual-stack network where supporting both IPv4 and IPv6 is necessary.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Research has shown that the use of fragmentation could be leveraged to evade network security controls, similar to IPv4.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] As a result, it is now required that the first fragment of an IPv6 packet contains the entire IPv6 header chain, such that some very pathological fragmentation cases are forbidden.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Additionally, as a result of research on the evasion of RA-Guard, the use of fragmentation is deprecated with Neighbor Discovery, and discouraged with Secure Neighbor Discovery (SEND).
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Due to the anticipated global growth of the Internet, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in the early 1990s started an effort to develop a next generation IP protocol.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By the beginning of 1992, several proposals appeared for an expanded Internet addressing system and by the end of 1992 the IETF announced a call for white papers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In September 1993, the IETF created a temporary, ad hoc *IP Next Generation* (IPng) area to deal specifically with such issues.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The new area was led by Allison Mankin and Scott Bradner, and had a directorate with 15 engineers from diverse backgrounds for direction-setting and preliminary document review: The working-group members were J.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The Internet Engineering Task Force adopted the IPng model on 25 July 1994, with the formation of several IPng working groups.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By 1996, a series of RFCs was released defining Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6), starting with RFC 1883.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The first RFC to standardize IPv6 was the RFC 1883 in 1995.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In 1998 RFC 2460 became the RFC for IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In July 2017 RFC 2460 was superseded by RFC 8200, which elevated IPv6 to "Internet Standard" (the highest maturity level for IETF protocols)..
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] RFC 8201 is a related IPv6 standard that describes how to discover the most efficient network path from source to destination that has the largest packet size permitted to avoid IP packet fragmentation, and thus maintain packet transmission performance.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The 1993 introduction of Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) in the routing and IP address allocation for the Internet, and the extensive use of network address translation (NAT), delayed IPv4 address exhaustion to allow for IPv6 deployment, which began in the mid-2000s.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Universities were among the early adopters of IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Virginia Tech deployed IPv6 at a trial location in 2004 and later expanded IPv6 deployment across the campus network.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By 2016, 82% of the traffic on their network used IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Imperial College London began experimental IPv6 deployment in 2003 and by 2016 the IPv6 traffic on their networks averaged between 20% and 40%.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A significant portion of this IPv6 traffic was generated through their high energy physics collaboration with CERN, which relies entirely on IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The Domain Name System (DNS) has supported IPv6 since 2008.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In the same year, IPv6 was first used in a major world event during the Beijing 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By 2011, all major operating systems in use on personal computers and server systems had production-quality IPv6 implementations.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Cellular telephone systems presented a large deployment field for Internet Protocol devices as mobile telephone service made the transition from 3G to 4G technologies, in which voice is provisioned as a voice over IP (VoIP) service that would leverage IPv6 enhancements.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In 2009, the US cellular operator Verizon released technical specifications for devices to operate on its "next-generation" networks.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The specification mandated IPv6 operation according to the *3GPP Release 8 Specifications (March 2009)*, and deprecated IPv4 as an optional capability.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] The deployment of IPv6 in the Internet backbone continued.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In 2018 only 25.3% of the about 54,000 autonomous systems advertised both IPv4 and IPv6 prefixes in the global Border Gateway Protocol (BGP) routing database.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] A further 243 networks advertised only an IPv6 prefix.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Internet backbone transit networks offering IPv6 support existed in every country globally, except in parts of Africa, the Middle East and China.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] By mid-2018 some major European broadband ISPs had deployed IPv6 for the majority of their customers.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Sky UK provided over 86% of its customers with IPv6, Deutsche Telekom had 56% deployment of IPv6, XS4ALL in the Netherlands had 73% deployment and in Belgium the broadband ISPs VOO and Telenet had 73% and 63% IPv6 deployment respectively.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In the United States the broadband ISP Xfinity had an IPv6 deployment of about 66%.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] In 2018 Xfinity reported an estimated 36.1 million IPv6 users, while AT&T reported 22.3 million IPv6 users.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] As of June 2026, Google's statistics show that approximately 50% of users access Google services over IPv6 native connectivity.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] Adoption varies significantly by region, with countries such as India, France, and Germany reporting adoption rates exceeding 70%, while others lag behind.
[src:thread-matter/ipv6] There is a peering dispute occurring between Hurricane Electric and Cogent Communications on IPv6, with the two network providers refusing to peer.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Matter originated in December 2019 as the Project Connected Home over IP (CHIP) working group, founded by Amazon, Apple, Google, and the Connectivity Standards Alliance (when it was the Zigbee Alliance).
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Subsequent members include IKEA, Huawei, Heiman, and Schneider.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Version 1.0 of the specification was published on 4 October 2022.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] The Matter software development kit is open-source under the Apache License.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] A software development kit (SDK) is provided royalty-free, though the ability to commission a finished product into a Matter network in the field mandates certification and membership fees, entailing both one-time, recurring, and per-product costs.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] This is enforced using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and so-called device attestation certificates.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Matter-compatible software updates for many existing hubs became available in late 2022, with Matter-enabled devices and software updates starting to release in 2023.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] The primary goal of Matter is to improve interoperability for the current smart home ecosystem.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] CSA and its members aim for the Matter logo to become ubiquitous and for consumers to instantly recognise it as a smart home device that will "just work".
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] However, Matter logos do not imply that devices will "just work"; infrastructure is also still required for full functionality, like a Wi-Fi network (which may need to be dual-band) and a Matter controller, and often, an app for each kind of device.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] In December 2019, Amazon, Apple, Google, Samsung SmartThings and the Zigbee Alliance announced the collaboration and formation of the working group of Project Connected Home over IP.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] The goal of the project is to simplify development for smart home product brands and manufacturers while increasing the compatibility of the products for consumers.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] The standard operates on Internet Protocol (IP) and functions via one or more controllers that connect and manage devices within a local network, eliminating the need for multiple proprietary hubs for each ecosystem.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Matter-certified products are engineered to operate locally and do not depend on an internet connection for their core functions.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Leveraging IPv6 addressing, the standard facilitates seamless communication with cloud services.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Its goal is to facilitate interoperability among smart home devices, mobile apps, and cloud services, employing a specific suite of IP-based networking technologies such as mDNS and IPv6.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] By adhering to a network design that operates at the Application Layer of the OSI 7 layer model, Matter differs from protocols like Zigbee or Z-Wave and theoretically can function on any IPv6-enabled network.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Presently, official support is limited to Wi-Fi, Ethernet, and the wireless mesh network Thread.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Updates to the standard are planned to occur biannually.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] For future versions, the working group has been working on support for ambient motion and presence sensing, environmental sensing and controls, closure sensors, energy management, Wi-Fi access points, cameras, and major appliances.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] CSA maintains the official list of Matter-certified products, and restricts use of the Matter logo to certified devices.
[src:thread-matter/matter-standard] Matter product certification is also stored on the CSA's Distributed Compliance Ledger (DCL), which publishes attestation information about certified devices.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] In July 2014, the Thread Group alliance was formed as an industry group to develop, maintain and drive adoption of Thread as an industry networking standard for IoT applications.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] Thread Group provides certification for components and products to ensure adherence to the spec.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] Initial members were ARM Holdings, Big Ass Solutions, NXP Semiconductors/Freescale, Google-subsidiary Nest Labs, OSRAM, Samsung, Silicon Labs, Somfy, Tyco International, Qualcomm, and the Yale lock company.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] In August 2018, Apple joined the group, and released its first Thread product, the HomePod Mini, in late 2020.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] The Thread protocol specification is available at no cost.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] Thread uses IPv6 over Low-Power Wireless Personal Area Networks (6LoWPAN), which, in turn, uses LR-WPAN as defined by the IEEE 802.15.4 wireless protocol with mesh communication (in the 2.4 GHz spectrum), as do Zigbee and other systems.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] However, Thread is IP-addressable, with cloud access and AES encryption.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] A BSD-licensed open-source implementation of Thread called *OpenThread* is available from and managed by Google.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] The OpenThread network simulator, a part of the OpenThread implementation, simulates Thread networks using OpenThread POSIX instances.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] The simulator utilises discrete-event simulation and allows for visualisation of communications through a web interface.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] A Thread border router is a device that provides bidirectional Internet Protocol connectivity between a Thread network and another physical network, such as Wi-Fi or Ethernet.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] It enables communication between Thread devices and other local networks or the Internet.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] A Thread network is a low-power mesh network using the IEEE 802.15.4 protocol in the 2.4 GHz ISM radio band, and a border router translates between such a network another physical network, allows for service discovery across network boundaries, and enables external commissioning of Thread devices.
[src:thread-matter/thread-network-protocol] Without a border router, Thread devices would be isolated from other networks and the Internet.
